{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":21964,"record_hash":"sha256:f01f1c1e4b992305044328e94e978ffefacf3aed0164199502f9d9102fe37774","timestamp":"2026-05-10T21:23:06.762Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 8e596b\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 835\nOutput:\n# Requirements and Goals\n\n## Problem\n\nAI coding sessions contain useful provenance: prompts, assistant messages, tool\ncalls, plans, and generated context. Today that data lives in agent-specific\nlocal storage and is not connected to the Git repository in a portable way.\n\nGitMeta gives GitButler a Git-native place to store that context without\npolluting the worktree. GitButler needs a small capture layer that reads selected\nagent transcripts, normalizes them enough to store, and writes them through\nGitMeta.\n\n## POC Goals\n\nThe first milestone should prove the storage and command shape, not solve agent\ndiscovery or publishing.\n\n- Capture Codex and Claude JSONL transcripts from an explicit path.\n- Expose capture through a hidden, feature-gated CLI command.\n- Store redacted, shareable-ready `gitbutler:*` data in GitMeta.\n- Keep the data project-scoped by default so future branch/PR/commit references\n  can point to durable sessions.\n- Make repeated capture idempotent.\n- Keep code changes focused in `crates/but-agentlog` plus the smallest CLI\n  bridge.\n\nThe detailed implementation contract lives in\n[First POC Implementation Contract](first-poc-implementation.md).\n\n## Product Direction\n\nThe POC should point toward two later use cases:\n\n- session handoff across machines and agents after GitMeta exchange and resume\n  UX are designed\n- colleague/reviewer browsing through a future GitButler web view that can show\n  the prompts, responses, tool activity, and prompting quality behind a branch\n  or pull request\n\nThose use cases require project-scoped sessions plus future relationship keys.\nThey do not require branch inference in the POC.\n\n## Later Goals\n\n- Capture the current or recent AI coding session without an explicit path.\n- Prefer deterministic hook-style capture when an agent can provide an exact\n  transcript path or session id.\n- Search known agent locations, filtered by repository, when no exact input is\n  available.\n- Add Cursor only after Codex and Claude establish the shared shape. Cursor needs\n  a separate design pass because its normal chat history is local SQLite and its\n  official portable format is Markdown export.\n- Add GitMeta serialize/fetch/push/sync behavior only after privacy and product\n  behavior are explicit.\n\nAgent-specific discovery notes live in [Capture Workflow](capture-workflow.md).\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- No automatic background capture in the first milestone.\n- No heuristic session discovery in the first milestone.\n- No GitMeta serialization, push, fetch, or sync in the first milestone.\n- No branch, commit, change-id, or pull request inference in the first milestone.\n- No machine-wide scraping of AI tool storage.\n- No dependency on provider-specific crates such as `but-claude`.\n- No `meta:local:*` storage for the main session records; these records are meant\n  to support future handoff and sharing.\n- No transcript copies on branch, commit, change, or pull request targets.\n  Future targets should reference durable project session keys.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- What user-facing privacy controls should exist before shareable-ready\n  transcript contents are serialized or pushed?\n- Should capture default to `project` forever, or should future hooks add\n  explicit branch/change/commit relationship references?\n- What redaction policy is good enough before remote exchange?\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T21:23:06.762Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}